There are several risks involved with the Happy Hardcore online store project. The first risk involves a lack of consumer interest for the Happy Hardcore brand, resulting in low usage of the Happy Hardcore website. More importantly, there are security risks to consider when selecting the server that the website will be hosted on and how payments will be processed. If the payment method or the server is insecure, the website may be hacked and customer information may be leaked.

Other initial risks include the costs of investing in the t-shirts. Up front costs can be a risk if those investments do not pay off later. A potentially fatal risk would be the tainted name of the brand. It is not in the brand’s best interest to relate itself to anything that has a negative connotation.
As a result the Happy Hardcore brand equity will be negatively impacted and even more difficult to recover the lost equity.

Happy Hardcore’s Website’s Business Case
Compiled by Team Jammin’


1.0 Introduction/Background
Happy Hardcore is a clothing line focused on a more happy and lighthearted street design and brand. Inspired by the Johnny Cupcake clothing line and his love for fine t-shirts, the Owner, Derrick Huey, decided to start the business as an entrepreneurial journey and design outlet for his last year in college.

2.0 Business Objective
Happy Hardcore’s strategic goals are to obtain brand awareness and to allow consumers a one-stop shop where they can purchase T-shirts and sweatshirts.  The Happy Hardcore website will allow users to purchase online with speed and ease.  It will also create brand awareness because the website itself will contain the brand name and will be one of the search results when typing in “Happy Hardcore” within the search engine. The website will create a more personal shopping experience with additional features such as a blog, video sharing, and an about section.

3.0 Current Situation and Problem/Opportunity Statement
Currently, the Happy Hardcore Website is under construction and a rough layout has been set it in place. However, there is no way of purchasing the products from the website.  The primary benefit of the Website is that it will allow consumers to browse through all the company’s products and make purchases directly from the site.  The opportunity to create an online store for the company’s products will reduce storing costs and allow consumers to spread the website through the Web creating more traffic to the site. The website will also provide information about the Happy Hardcore brand, and include a blog and a video section.

4.0 Critical Assumption and Constraints
The Happy Hardcore website must be a valuable asset for the Happy Hardcore brand. The website must be secure and accessible to all users with an Internet connection. All customer payment information must be secure. The website should be easy to update and require minimal technical support. The project management team, Team Jammin’, must lead the effort in this project. In addition to the project management team, the project must include participants from Happy Hardcore.

5.0 Analysis of Options and Recommendation
There are three options for addressing this opportunity:

1. Do nothing.  This will result in a failed business because any consumer who wants to purchase has no way of obtaining it because their is no physical store selling the product.

2. Use a third-party payment service such as PayPal, however this will reduce potential profit because the third-party payment service will ask for a percentage of the profit.

3. The company could create their own payment service, but then the risk of a hack and sensitive information being compromised increases, but potential profit will not be reduced because no third-party service would be used.


6.0 Preliminary Project Requirements
Some of the main features regarding the web store will be initialized by:

1. To get a better understating to market strategies and appropriate display interfaces, there will need to be some extensive research done.

2. The over look and aesthetic feel for the web store should be simple and easy to navigate through for the audience.

3. The product owner wants to make sure that the web site does an accurate job of reflecting the meaning and attitude of the brand. This can be done by featuring some of the main articles of clothing (mainly shirts).

4. The product owner also requested to include additional features such as blogs, video forums, and an background information section. This allows the owner to create a culture for the brand, and a forum where the audience can share their opinions and thoughts.

5. The method of payment is up to deliberation. The most viable option is to use a third party member to assist with payment transactions.

7.0 Budget Estimate and Financial Analysis
For the initial costs for getting Happy Hardcore up an running, a estimate maximum total of $3000 will be invested into the clothing line. That means a estimate of $1000 per month will be invested into the company until the expected launch date. The T-shirts cost an estimate of $8 to $10 each to produce. Though the pricing of the shirts are not yet finalized, the shirts are looking to be sold at around $25-$30 each. The amount of T-shirts estimated to be produced is 100. That would make about $1000 for the cost of the production of the T-shirts by the expected launch date.

8.0 Schedule Estimate
Owner Derrick Huey has indicated that he would like to have Happy Hardcore’s website to premiere in Spring of 2012.  This gives us approximately 10 weeks to plan, design, develop, and implement the website.  Derrick has a preliminary sketch and layout of how he wants the site to look so we will devote the majority of out team’s time and effort on the web storefront.  

9.0 Potential Risks
There are several risks involved with the Happy Hardcore online store project. The first risk involves a lack of consumer interest for the Happy Hardcore brand, resulting in low usage of the Happy Hardcore website. More importantly, there are security risks to consider when selecting the server that the website will be hosted on and how payments will be processed. If the payment method or the server is insecure, the website may be hacked and customer information may be leaked.

Other initial risks include the costs of investing in the t-shirts. Up front costs can be a risk if those investments do not pay off later. A potentially fatal risk would be the tainted name of the brand. It is not in the brand’s best interest to relate itself to anything that has a negative connotation.
